gggenomes是共线性分析并作图的R脚本
示例文件：
1. emale_seqs: Sequence index of 6 EMALE genomes (endogenous virophages)，A data set containing the sequence information on 6 endogenous virophages found in the genomes of the marine protist Cafeteria burkhardae.
1. emale_genes：Gene annotations of 6 EMALE genomes (endogenous virophages)。由GFF文件而来！
emale_ava：使用minimap2进行all-versus-all序列比对
2. emale_cogs: Clusters of orthologs of 6 EMALE proteomes
3. emale_gc： Relative GC-content along 6 EMALE genomes
4. 
5. emale_ngaros: Integrated Ngaro retrotransposons of 6 EMALE genomes
6. emale_prot_ava: All-versus-all alignments 6 EMALE proteomes，使用blast输出结果https://github.com/seqan/lambda/wiki/BLAST-Output-Formats
7. emale_prot_uniref50：Alignments of 6 EMALE proteomes against Uniref50；One row per alignment. 使用 mmseqs2 (blast-like)进行序列比对, and filtered by evalue (<1e-20).

9. emale_tirs:Terminal inverted repeats of 6 EMALE genomes,由GFF文件而来！

How to do the synteny analysis?
Step1: 

Step2: convert the gbk file to bed file using the perl script "2_convert_gbk_to_bed.pl"
# https://github.com/maxmicrobe/POP-seq/blob/main/gbk2bed.pl

module load bioperl
perl convert_gbk_to_bed.pl input.gbk > output.bed

In this command:
perl convert_gbk_to_bed.pl is the command to run your Perl script.
input.gbk should be replaced with the path to your input GenBank file.
output.bed is the name you want to give to the BED file that will be created. You can choose any name you like for the output file, just make sure it has the ".bed" file extension.
When you run the script with this command, the script's output (which is the BED-formatted data) will be saved in the output.bed file in the same directory where you execute the command. You can then access and use the generated BED file as needed.
